blog.name: pokegodsandmissingno
blog.title: P̵o̵K̸é̴G̸o̸D̷s̸ and Frightful Things to Come?
blog.description: There is a growing desire and expectation of humans here on Earth in making full contact with PoKéMoN who are still unknown. Back in 1995, when I saw my first UPM (Unindexed Pocket Monster), I found out very quickly that other people thought you were totally crazy if you said you saw such things. The world has changed quite a bit since then when I was a child. In fact, in late 1997, a poll taken in Kanto shows that for the first time ever, more than fifty percent of residents now believe in PokéGODS's. Since then, there have been polls that put the figure at over eighty percent or more.

summary: Pokemon Card of the Day #1550: Landorus (Noble Victories)
title: Pokemon Card of the Day #1550: Landorus (Noble Victories)
body:
Landorus was another Basic Fighting-type Pokemon to consider at a time where good Pokemon that struggled against the type were very common. Landorus was notable for being able to help itself get going early in the game! This made it pretty intriguing. It also didn’t have quite as much power as Terrakion, which was annoying. It still had plenty of potential, since there was the chance of getting a Landorus going on turn 2 and the power at that point of the game wasn’t bad at all.

110 HP was pretty solid. It was just high enough to combine with the Lightning Resistance to take a Bolt Strike from Zekrom. There was that x2 Water Weakness that could be an issue against Vanilluxe, Empoleon, Kyurem, and Keldeo EX, and that could be a problem in certain match-ups where Terrakion would have held its own a bit better. Landorus did have a big advantage over its main competition by needing only a single Energy to retreat. This meant that Switch wasn’t completely required when using this card. It was a nice change from the norm when it came to big Fighting-types.

Abundant Harvest required a Fighting Energy and let you attach a basic Energy card from your discard pile to Landorus. This let Landorus get going on turn 2 if you started with it, which was a big help. There were plenty of Pokemon that could get going on turn 2, of course, but Landorus was notable for being a Fighting-type with at least a little acceleration.

Gaia Hammer required 3 Fighting and a Colorless Energy. The 80 damage here was pretty solid, and enough to take down a Zekrom, but it was sadly just short of taking down a Darkrai EX at full health. The attack also did 10 damage to each Benched Pokemon for both players, which could soften things up. It also softened up your own team. There was the option of playing this alongside the big dragons to take advantage of Outrage like Donphan occasionally did. Landorus did more damage on the same turn if all went well but was more Energy-intensive.

Landorus wasn’t as useful as Terrakion as a big Fighting-type attacker due to its slightly lower power being an issue against one of its main targets. The Bench damage was cool but also hurt your own Pokemon. That being said, there was an argument for trying out Landorus in certain decks that wanted Donphan. Donphan was bulkier and took less Energy to work but Landorus was a Basic Pokemon. This made it marginally competitive but not anything that would blow you away.
